    "awards": [
        {
            "title": "Honorable Mention in Panhellenic Architectural Competition \"Restoration of the Old Port of Patras\"",
            "description": "Team: Konstantinos Alexopoulos, Annita Douka, Ioanna Koulouri, Grigoris Koutropoulos, Nikos Spyrou\n\nThe old port of Patras which is currently neither a vivid accessible public space nor an active port, is awaiting to become actually inhabited by its citizens through an intervention which could redefine the spatial character of the area. The proposal is elaborating on new ways of prosthetic fabrics in the Mediterranean Coast for a new ecology of inhabitation of the 21st century. A new flexible landscape is proposed through new coastal-urban infrastructural interventions on port and piers as well as in the waterscape. New technologies, energy capture from physical forces as well as Patras\u2019 need for green space are added to the existing port landscape, which is considered as a preservable urban monument.\n\nThe proposal consists of two infrastructural prosthetic structures: \nA coastal infrastructure composed by a hybrid structure, partly honeycomb for semi-transparent units, pots of greenery and solid surfaces, creating space beneath and on top of it for different activities.\nA flexible network of floating units in the harbor basins that composes a transformable archipelago depending on seasonal needs or temporary events. The different units typologies for assembling makes mass production the preferred way of fabrication and is serving transformability.\n\nThe proposed intervention is using self-sufficient mechanisms which are using natural means for energy and watering needs. More specifically, small floating units of Pelamis Type technology are located outside of the breakwater, capturing wave\u2019s kinetic energy and transform it to electricity. Moreover, a watering network from rainwater is embedded on the proposal; these are collected by the solid areas of the structure and lead to basins which serve as structural supportings for the infrastructure. The different types of vegetation for Mediterranean areas adjust the microclimate as well as the infrastructure itself.",
            "issuer": "Architects Association of the Achaia Prefecture",
            "date": {
                "month": 6,
                "day": null,
                "year": 2016
            }
        }
    ],
